1235","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","1197":"1197","1250":"1250","1307":"1307","Montgomery, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"en":{"1220–":"1220–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1275–1374":"1275–1374","1200–1307":"1200–1307","1197–Female":"1197–Deceased","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","1197":"1197","1250":"1250","1307":"1307","Montgomery, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales","Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Samuel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Raj, Varughese, Ashok, Babu, Eapen, Mathai, Saji, Aleykutty, Arul, Arun, Asha, Beena.","English, Scottish, Welsh, German, Dutch, Spanish, French, Slovak, Czech, Jewish, and African (mainly Nigeria and Ethiopia); Hungarian (<b>Sámuel</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Samuel</i> (Hebrew <i>Shemuel</i> ‘Name of God’). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages such as Greek patronymic <b>Samouelidis</b>. The name <i>Samuel</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Moilanen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Eino, Oiva, Jaana, Rauha, Reino, Toivo, Tyyne, Waino, Wiljo, Yalmer.","Finnish: from the Karelian personal name <i>Moila</i> (a form of   Samuel  ) + the suffix <i>-nen</i>. This is aneastern Finnish surname dating back to the 16th century."]},{"name":"Samu","meanings":["Hungarian (also <b>Sámu</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Sámuel</i>; see   Samuel  .","Indian: unexplained.","African (mainly Sierra Leone, Malawi, and Zimbabwe): unexplained."]},{"name":"Samec","meanings":["Czech and Slovak: from <i>samec</i> ‘male’ (an animal), probably used as a nickname for a strong, energetic man.","Czech: possibly also from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  .","Slovenian: nickname for a loner or topographic name for someone who lived in a secluded spot, from <i>samec</i> ‘loner, solitary person’, also ‘bachelor’. Alternatively, it may be from <i>samec</i> ‘male’ (an animal); compare Czech and Slovak name above."]},{"name":"Sammis","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuels","meanings":["English and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Samuel  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Samel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Moshe, Yetta.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samek","meanings":["Czech: from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuelian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Armenian Hagop, Haroutune, Hovsep, Kourken, Siranoush, Souren, Vartan, Vartkes.  French Arsene, Marielle.","Armenian: patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  , a western Armenian variant of <i>Samvel</i>. This form of the surname is found mainly in the US (and also in Lebanon and France); in Armenia it is spelled <b>Samvelyan</b>."]},{"name":"Samelson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Kalmen, Moty, Pinchas.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuelsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Sig, Thor.  German Gunter.","Danish and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  ."]}]},{"name":"Madoc","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[{"name":"Madog","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madoc Ap Samuel was born in 1220, in Anglesey, Wales, his father, Samuel ap Cadafael, was 21 and his mother, Eigyr verch Madog, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Eva verch Maredudd."},"et":{"1220–":"1220–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1275–1374":"1275–1374","1200–1307":"1200–1307","119